<Default title="About · Harshith Kantamneni" description="GPU systems engineer building autonomous AI labs." current="about">

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-parallax-layer hero-parallax-layer-1" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="hero-parallax-layer hero-parallax-layer-2" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container">
      <span class="index-number">About</span>
      <h1 style="max-width: 18ch;">Engineer. Lab builder.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        I came up through GPU performance engineering: CUDA kernel optimization,
        memory hierarchy reverse engineering, gem5 calibration, and ML-driven systems
        work, with two NVIDIA DLI certifications along the way. Since early 2026 I
        have been running autonomous AI labs as a parallel research effort.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="padding-top: 0;">
    <div class="grid-editorial">

      <article class="body">
        <h2>The current work</h2>
        <p>
          I design and run autonomous AI labs on commodity hardware (a single
          MacBook, M3 Pro, 18 GB RAM). Each one is a persistent organization of
          specialist agents with memory, evaluators, red-team review, and structured
          artifacts, working across long horizons on a specific kind of problem.
          Some focus on product engineering. Some focus on research operations.
          New ones get added as they come online.
        </p>
        <p>
          The structural challenge that turns out to matter most is not model
          capability. It is verification. When a system grades itself, the
          verification surface drifts, gets gamed, and collapses. I document this
          pattern and the structural fixes for it across reports, notes, and the
          lab modules themselves.
        </p>

        <h2>Background</h2>
        <p>
          UW-Madison, ECE. Computer architecture, GPU performance, ML systems.
          Coursework and projects covered cycle-level architectural simulation, GPU
          memory systems, ABFT-GEMM reliability, ML-guided CUDA optimization, and
          task-graph partitioning. Industry work in GPU performance benchmarking and
          HPC pipelines.
        </p>
        <p>
          Increasingly persuaded that the interesting frontier is not model
          capability at the peak. It is the operational discipline that lets
          autonomous AI systems do long-horizon work without collapsing into
          Goodhart-style failure modes. That is where my GPU and systems background
          applies in unexpected ways. Long-running multi-agent labs need careful
          resource accounting, memory hierarchy management, and performance
          discipline.
        </p>

        <h2>What I publish</h2>
        <ul style="padding-left: var(--space-5); line-height: var(--lh-body);">
          <li><strong>Reports.</strong> Long-form methodology pieces, single-system case studies, and failure-mode catalogs (around one per month)</li>
          <li><strong>Notes.</strong> Short observations from running the labs (three to five per week)</li>
          <li><strong>Lab modules.</strong> Public truth and operating model for each running lab</li>
          <li><strong>Templates.</strong> Reusable artifacts (cycle briefs, evaluator checklists, falsifier ledgers)</li>
          <li><strong>Now.</strong> What I am working on this week</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Get in touch</h2>
        <p>
          Email is the primary surface. The <a href="/contact">contact page</a>
          has the full set of channels and what I respond to.
        </p>
      </article>

